      <VALUE>I.  EFFECTIVE DATE OF VALUATION

The effective date of the appraisal is November 24, 2020, which coincides with the date valuation included in this report. 

II. INTENDED USE/INTENDED USER:

The Intended User of this appraisal report is the Lender/Client. The Intended Use is to evaluate the property that is the subject of this appraisal for a mortgage finance transaction, subject to the stated Scope of Work, purpose of the appraisal, reporting requirements of this appraisal report form, and Definition of Market Value.  No additional Intended Users are identified by the appraiser.  

III. INSPECTION DISCLOSURE:

It should also be noted that this appraisal is not a home inspection, and that the appraiser is not a qualified home inspector.  The appraiser performed only a visual inspection of the accessible areas of the building.  This appraisal cannot be relied upon to disclose conditions and/or defects in the property.  Only a qualified home inspection professional/environmental inspector can be relied upon for such information. 

IV.  SCOPE OF THE APPRAISAL 

The following steps were taken in arriving at the final estimate of value stated in the attached appraisal report: 

1. Upon receipt of the assignment, a preliminary search of all available resources was made to determine market trends, influences and other factors pertinent to the subject. 
 
2. A physical inspection of the property was performed by your appraiser.  Although diligence was exercised in the inspection, your appraiser does not claim to be an expert on such matters as pest control, structural engineering, hazardous wastes, mechanical inspections, etc. and no warranty is given as to these items.  As needed, inspections by professionals in these fields might be recommended with the final value estimate. 
 
3. A second review of all data was completed with the most  pertinent factors weighed and considered.  Comparable sales were inspected externally, and in some cases internally, the sales data was verified with a party to the transaction. 
 
4. This appraisal report was completed in accordance with the standards dictated by 
THE APPRAISAL FOUNDATION and specific lender guidelines.  The report includes all data and information needed to lead the reader to a similar conclusion of value. 
 
5. Completion of the assignment was considered the delivery of the report. 

V.   COMPLIANCE WITH STANDARDS OF PRACTICE 

It is the intention of your appraiser to comply with the Uniform Standards of Professional Appraisal Practice as adopted by the Appraisal Foundation as of the Current Edition.  

VI.  COMPETENCY OF THE APPRAISER 

Your appraiser, L. Ann Tedeschi, has the appropriate knowledge and experience to complete this assignment competently, and has been devoting her full time career to real estate appraisal assignments since April 1994. Prior to that, she devoted her career to doing mass appraisal for the Okanogan County Assessor's Office. The type  of properties appraised included single and multi family residences and specializes in waterfront homes, recreational properties, high end, new construction, unique properties and expert testimony. Attached to this report you will find a copy of your appraiser's qualification resume. 


VII.  SALES HISTORY

There is currently no sale pending, nor current listing activity on the subject property. The subject property was purchased by the current owners on 5/16/2018 for $324,900 and the lot was purchased by the builder on 11/21/2017 for $76,900. These are the only noted sales or transfers of the subject property in the past 36 months.   

VIII.  RENTS AND VACANCIES 

At the present time, the subject is located in a predominately owner occupied year round neighborhood, for this reason the income approach is not used in this report.

IX.  TREND ANALYSIS 

The subject market is strong demand in and limited availability of homes in the subject's search parameters which could decrease marketing times.  The subject is expected to market in a period of 2 to 4 months at the appraised value.  This information was obtained through the North West Washington Multiple Listing Service statistics and interviews with several local Realtor/Brokers as well as observations by your appraiser and members of their firm.

X.  DEDUCTIONS AND DISCOUNTS 

This appraisal report has been made considering the property in "AS IS" condition, as of the date of valuation, without unrealistic assumptions and with clearly outlined recommendations for repairs, inspections, and consideration for marketing discounts.  The highest and best use, as improved, is in conformity with current zoning and land uses in the area.  All  comparable sales were investigated to determine sales discounts if applicable, and were reported as such. 

XI.  PROHIBITED INFLUENCES 

The appraisal assignment was not accepted based upon a minimum valuation, specific valuation, or loan approval.  Neither present nor future employment of the appraiser was conditioned upon the appraisal producing a specific value or value range, nor any loan approval conditions. 

XII.  APPRAISAL REPORT 

This appraisal is intended to be an Appraisal Report document containing sufficient information necessary to enable the reader to understand the opinion of value.  Any third party studies referred to have been verified by the appraiser to the extend the assumptions used. This appraisal report is prepared for the sole and exclusive use of the client to assist with the property valuation decisions.  It is not to be relied upon by any other third  party or parties for any purpose whatsoever without the express written permission of the appraiser.

XIII.  PERSONAL PROPERTY 

Any personal property involved in the transaction has been excluded from the valuation.  Should a transaction include personal property sufficient in value to affect market value, an assessment of this situation will be noted in the report with a recommendation for further action. 

XIV.  THREE APPROACHES TO VALUE 

Your appraiser has made a reasonable effort to employ the three recognized approaches to value.  Single family residences are not typically purchased for investment purposes, therefore, if the income approach is not used, it is considered to be less accurate and reliable than the cost or market approach, due to lack of sufficient information. 


XV.  HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES OR MATERIALS

Unless otherwise stated in this report, the existence of hazardous substances, including without limitation, asbestos, polychlorinated biphenyls, petroleum leakage, or agricultural chemicals, which may or may not be present on the property, or other adverse environmental conditions, were not observed nor were called to the attention of your appraiser upon inspection of the subject property.  Your appraiser has no knowledge of the existence of such materials on or in the property unless otherwise stated.  It should be noted, however, that your appraiser is not qualified to test such substances or conditions, so no responsibility is assumed for any such conditions, nor for any expertise or engineering knowledge required to discover them.  The client is urged to retain an expert in the field of environmental impacts upon real estate if so desired.

Included following is an Environmental Checklist for Residential Real Property:

A.  Site Use/History

Is there any indication that the residential property has been used for commercial or industrial purposes?  NO

Do any adjacent or nearby properties have or appear to have toxic/environmental problems? NO

B.  House and/or On-site Structures

Do any buildings appear to have asbestos-containing materials (i.e., asbestos shingles, pipe insulation, spray-on ceilings prior to 1979, old vinyl tile)?  NO

Are there any parts of the house or other buildings on site which are used or may have been used for the storage of drums or other than household-size chemical containers (i.e., oils paints pesticides, etc)? NO

If yes to the above question, have any floor drains been observed in the buildings in question?

C.  Outdoor Areas

Are there any underground storage tanks apparent on the site? NO

Are there any areas observed with stains on the ground or with suspect dead or excessive stressed vegetation (other than those caused by legal garden chemicals or lack of water)?  NO

Are there any drainage sumps or other surface water channels observed on the property? NO

Are there any major debris, trash or junk disposal areas observed on the property?  NO

To the best of the appraiser's knowledge, the existence of any observed condition (checked with yes) does not have an impact on marketability as of the date of appraisal unless otherwise noted in the appraisal report.

The answers provided for completion of this checklist are based on visual observations undertaken as a part of the normal field inspection of the property by the appraiser or otherwise documentable indications of the site conditions.  The appraiser is not qualified to confirm or deny the existence of hazardous conditions, and completion of this checklist is not to be construed as such confirmation or denial.  Confirmation of site conditions relative to hazardous materials and/or wastes would require assessment by a duly qualified professional with direct training and experience in environmental assessment of real property.

The appraiser is not a home inspector not a qualified environmental inspector. The appraisal does not guarantee that the property is free of defects o r environmental hazards. The appraiser performs a cursory inspection of those visible and accessible areas only. Mold, mildew, asbestos or other environmental hazards may be present in the home, and only a qualified, home inspection professional or an environmental inspector can be considered qualified to recognize these potentially hazardous materials.
XVI.  CONDITION OF SYSTEMS:

This appraiser does not attest to the working condition of the mechanical systems, including but not limited to heating, cooling, plumbing and/or appliances of the subject residence.

Although this appraiser may not have noted any apparent signs of infestation, your appraiser is not an expert in this field.  It is the appraiser's opinion that only an expert in the field of pest inspection may be relied upon for this information.

XVII.  MARKET ADJUSTMENTS DISCUSSED: 

Wherever possible, adjustments to the individual comparable sales were made by bracketing the subject with respect to the individual item, (i.e. size, site and site characteristics, age and effective age, quality, room counts and amenities, etc.), In this way, the adjustments can be extracted from the comparable sales used in the analysis.  Where large individual adjustments are unavoidable due to the absence of comparable sales which closely match the subject, additional supporting data, (matched pair sales, additional comparable sales), will be included if available.

Smaller adjustments to reflect the variations in amenities found in the market which cannot be measured by a matched pair sales analysis are based upon the appraiser's subjective judgment. The appraiser has made every attempt to bracket the subject with respect to value thereby analyzing properties both inferior and superior to the subject property.  Although the appraiser recognizes that this type of "bracketing" is considered good appraisal practice, it is not always possible to achieve.  When this occurs, additional supporting data will be provided.

In prioritizing the selection of comparable sales, physical characteristics of the comparable sale are given the most emphasis, followed by comparability of site, date of sale, and proximity to the subject property.  Effective age of the subject and the comparable sales is estimated by the appraiser based upon personal inspection where possible and by interview with sellers, purchasers, Realtors, and/or other appraisers familiar with the properties.

Above grade square footage adjustments were made on a "per square foot" basis based upon size, quality and function.  Typically, no adjustment is made where less than 100 square feet exists between the subject and the comparable sale as it is unlikely that even a knowledgeable purchaser recognizes a difference of less than 100 square feet in the typical residence.  No adjustments are made for bedroom counts, as they are considered in the improved square footage, unless functional utility is determined to be a detriment in the current market and further explained.  Bathrooms are adjusted separately and additionally to square footage adjustments.  

 
The following adjustments were made consistently throughout this report: 

Square footage is adjusted at $150/SF based approximately 65% of the $235/SF (for any value over $20,323) noted on the single line linear regression analysis. Quality is adjusted at $10/SF, includes quality of finish materials and custom built-ins and/or upgrades and is based on the difference in sale prices of Comps #1 & 3 and the matched pair noted on the Single Line Linear Regression Analysis contained in the addendum. This includes other items such as fireplaces, outdoor living areas, etc. and any other items not individually adjusted for. The remaining 35% is attributed to the site, site improvements, garages and sheds.
ADDITIONAL COMMENTS: 

Inspection Disclosure:

It should also be noted that this appraisal is not a home inspection, and that the appraiser is not a qualified home inspector.  The appraiser performed only a visual inspection of the accessible areas of the building.  This appraisal cannot be relied upon to disclose conditions and/or defects in the property.  Only a qualified home inspection professional/environmental inspector can be relied upon for such information. 

Comparable Sales:

Professional appraisal practice requires that the appraiser utilize the best comparable sales available as of the effective date of the appraisal.  This includes sales within the most recent time frame and those within the closest proximity to the subject property.  However, in some cases, the best sale comparisons are found in sales that are older and more distant than considered allowable by typical lending standards.

It should be noted that your appraiser has completed a thorough search of the market in the subject location and has considered all of the recent sales in the subject's, neighborhood and community.  Every attempt has been made to compare and analyze sales within one year and one mile proximity to the subject property.  However, in some cases, lack of truly comparable, recent sales forces the appraiser to utilize older and/or more distant sales.  If this is the case, the adjustments to these sales have been fully considered and based upon true market data.

Comparable Sales Photos:

In some instances, the comparable sales photos used in this appraisal may have been copied  from the MLS published listing photos.  When this occurs, it is based upon the appraiser's opinion that the  MLS photo is likely the best available photo available to illustrate the condition of the residence and the property at the time of sale.  In the winter months, the appraiser may choose to use a MLS photo that illustrates the condition of the yard and landscaping while providing a good representation of the home without the obstruction of snow on the site.  In cases where the comparable sale has a gated driveway, an unsafe access, or "No Trespassing" signs, the appraiser may choose to utilize a photo from the MLS which best illustrates the home for comparison purposes.  

Privacy Policy:

In the course of performing appraisals, we may collect "nonpublic, personal information" about properties, homeowners and/or tenants.  This information is used to facilitate the appraisal services we provide, and may include information provided to us by the client, the homeowner, tenants or others.

Any nonpublic, personal information provided about a property, obtained in the process of appraisal inspection and/or appraisal research, will not be disclosed to any party other than the client without client permission, client authorization, or as required by law.  This privacy policy extends to our employees and any third party consultants we may employ.  Nonpublic information revealed as part of an appraisal assignment will be maintained in strict confidence within our firm.

We comply with the Uniform Standards of Professional Appraisal Practice work file retention requirements, and we retain our records for the required time period.  In order to protect any nonpublic information from unauthorized access, we maintain physical, electronic and procedural safeguards that insure the security and integrity of the information contained within our files.
